CuDwrjtz8sTlxicTMl2-VCrDyE_32hbpZ1Pqogirqx1XOL1lUdTPluBVjp9aLfEFMAdt22pJKErqfQxXmsHY31tOaHalbgPnXQVHiv1pXjI-HEMCxfEPtyYN_WLZqz1QUogVkXC0M6e_QwG75IEFfV4LWgjtG2D1GLBz9Kpztj3mgtTzGnlcLUXMwVQGkV-V33bBMs0Hbz4m5A8uDOZHM6F3U5MGMxCs=\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering DNS setup**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about how to manage the moving parts in my current setup. It seems that using a Direct DnsResolverLoader might reduce timing issues. Also, there's an active class the user might utilize internally. Maybe it’s worth considering combining the direct initialization with the public builder? There’s definitely a lot to think about when optimizing for performance and simplicity, especially with these internal classes. I’ll have to weigh the options carefully!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Setting up a server**\\\\n\\\\nI'm looking to create a resolver using bootstrap first. I'll need to bind the server to the loopback and use `com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpServer`. An async client is going to send requests, and I'll implement a response handler that collects status and body in the future. I also need SDK request classes to build the request. I’m wondering if I need a content publisher for the async request, especially for a GET method. I'd better check `AsyncExecuteRequest` for clarification.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_J4vGT38G6VrAm74dE0z6ddIQ|fc_02d5c131a9d80cf5016a28a5ff26088193875096a6b14af1fa\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"javap -classpath $(find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/software.amazon.awssdk/http-client-spi/2.34.0 -name '*.jar' | head -1) software.amazon.awssdk.http.async.AsyncExecuteRequest | sed -n '1,160p'; javap -classpath $(find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/software.amazon.awssdk/http-client-spi/2.34.0 -name '*.jar' | head -1) software.amazon.awssdk.http.async.SdkAsyncHttpResponseHandler | sed -n '1,160p'; javap -classpath $(find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/software.amazon.awssdk/http-client-spi/2.34.0 -name '*.jar' | head -1) software.amazon.awssdk.http.async.SdkAsyncHttpResponseHandler\\\\$Builder | sed -n '1,160p'\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 5545, \"output\": 1080, \"cacheRead\": 37888, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 44513, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1781048808111, \"responseId\": \"resp_02d5c131a9d80cf5016a28a5e8a83881939c88cd2043e7273f\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/software.amazon.awssdk:netty-nio-client:2.34.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-09T23-49-00-898659Z.log:2945:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering DNS setup**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to manage the moving parts in my current setup. It seems that using a Direct DnsResolverLoader might reduce timing issues. Also, there's an active class the user might utilize internally. Maybe it’s worth considering combining the direct initialization with the public builder? There’s definitely a lot to think about when optimizing for performance and simplicity, especially with these internal classes. I’ll have to weigh the options carefully!\\n\\n**Setting up a server**\\n\\nI'm looking to create a resolver using bootstrap first. I'll need to bind the server to the loopback and use `com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpServer`. An async client is going to send requests, and I'll implement a response handler that collects status and body in the future. I also need SDK request classes to build the request. I’m wondering if I need a content publisher for the async request, especially for a GET method. I'd better check `AsyncExecuteRequest` for clarification.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_02d5c131a9d80cf5016a28a5e94088819